---
/**
 * "What is a Qubit?" — Phase 2 flagship essay.
 *
 * 02-03 wired in: ProbabilityBars + StateVector + GateButtons + a per-page store
 * (key: "qubit-essay"). Bloch sphere widget (02-04) and rotation sliders +
 * annotations (02-05) land next. Final copy + a11y/perf pass in 02-06.
 */
import EssayLayout from "../layouts/EssayLayout.astro";
import MathBlock from "../components/MathBlock.astro";
import MathNerds from "../components/MathNerds.astro";
import ProbabilityBars from "../components/ProbabilityBars.astro";
import StateVector from "../components/StateVector.astro";
import GateButtons from "../components/GateButtons.astro";
import BlochSphere from "../components/BlochSphere/index.astro";

const KEY = "qubit-essay";
---

<EssayLayout
  title="What is a Qubit?"
  subtitle="A qubit is not a magical coin. It's a unit vector in a two-dimensional complex vector space — and you can poke it."
  description="An interactive introduction to qubits for working developers."
>
  <p>
    Forget the coin. Forget the cat. A qubit is a unit vector
    <code>(α, β)</code> with complex components, and almost everything
    interesting about quantum computing falls out of two facts: the
    vector can point in any direction in a 2D complex space, and gates
    are just rotations of that vector.
  </p>

  <p data-step="0">
    We'll build intuition by <strong>playing</strong>. Every widget on
    this page shares one simulator — change the state with a button and
    every visualization below updates.
  </p>

  <h2>Press a gate, watch the state</h2>

  <p data-step="1">
    Click <code>H</code> below. The Hadamard gate puts <code>|0⟩</code>
    into an equal superposition of <code>|0⟩</code> and <code>|1⟩</code>.
    Click <code>X</code> to flip. Click <code>Z</code> to phase-flip
    (and notice probabilities don't change). Click <code>H</code> twice
    in a row to return to where you started — H is its own inverse.
  </p>

  <GateButtons storeKey={KEY} qubits={1} gates={["H", "X", "Z"]} />
  <ProbabilityBars storeKey={KEY} qubits={1} caption="Probability of measuring each outcome" />
  <StateVector storeKey={KEY} qubits={1} caption="The amplitudes themselves" />

  <h2>The state vector</h2>
  <p data-step="2">
    Above, the readout shows the complex amplitudes <code>α</code> and
    <code>β</code>. Their squared magnitudes are the probabilities.
    Below, the same state has a geometric body: every qubit state is
    a point on the surface of a unit sphere. Drag the arrow tip.
  </p>

  <BlochSphere storeKey={KEY} caption="Drag the arrow tip. Apply a gate above and watch the arrow rotate." />

  <h2>Continuous rotation</h2>
  <p data-step="3">
    Discrete gates jump between named states. <strong>Rotation gates</strong>
    sweep continuously: drag a slider and watch the state smear from
    <code>|0⟩</code> to <code>|1⟩</code> and back. (Sliders + annotations
    land in 02-05.)
  </p>

  <div class="my-6 rounded-lg border border-dashed border-slate-700 bg-slate-900/40 p-6 text-center text-slate-500">
    [Rotation sliders — lands in 02-05]
  </div>

  <MathNerds title="What the gates are, formally">
    <p>A single qubit's state is a unit vector in <MathBlock display={false} tex="\\mathbb{C}^2" />:</p>
    <MathBlock tex="|\\psi\\rangle = \\alpha|0\\rangle + \\beta|1\\rangle, \\quad |\\alpha|^2 + |\\beta|^2 = 1" />
    <p>The Hadamard gate as a 2×2 matrix:</p>
    <MathBlock tex="H = \\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1\\\\1 & -1\\end{bmatrix}" />
    <p>Rotation about the X axis by θ:</p>
    <MathBlock tex="R_x(\\theta) = \\cos(\\theta/2)\\, I - i \\sin(\\theta/2)\\, X" />
  </MathNerds>

  <Fragment slot="math-nerds">
    <p>
      The Bloch sphere is the visualization of pure single-qubit states
      modulo global phase. Two states that differ only by a unit complex
      scalar are physically indistinguishable, so we represent a qubit
      as a point on the unit 2-sphere parameterized by (θ, φ):
    </p>
    <MathBlock tex="|\\psi\\rangle = \\cos(\\theta/2)\\,|0\\rangle + e^{i\\varphi}\\sin(\\theta/2)\\,|1\\rangle" />
    <p>
      All single-qubit gates are 2×2 unitaries, i.e. elements of U(2).
      Modulo a global phase, they're rotations of the Bloch sphere —
      that's why "rotation gates" is the right mental model, not "logic gates."
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="footer-nav">
    <a href="/" class="hover:text-slate-200">← Home</a>
    <span class="text-slate-600">Next: Superposition (coming in Phase 4)</span>
  </Fragment>
</EssayLayout>

<script>
  import { attachScrolly } from "../lib/scrolly";

  const root = document.querySelector("article");
  if (root) {
    attachScrolly(root, {
      stepSelector: "[data-step]",
      onStep: (i) => console.debug(`[scrolly] step ${i}`),
    });
  }
</script>
